//             Experiment No.5:  Applying CSS Styling to Web Pages

a. Learn how to apply inline CSS to style individual HTML elements. 
b. Learn how to use internal CSS for styling multiple elements within a single HTML page. 
c. Learn how to use external CSS to maintain a separate stylesheet for consistent styling across web pages.

INLINE

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Inline CSS</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1 style="color: #0f0a4ff; background-color: lightgray; border: 2px solid black;">Inline Styling Heading</h1>
</body>
</html>

INTERNAL

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Internal CSS</title>
    <style>
        h1 {
            color: red;
            background-color: lightyellow;
            border: 3px dashed green;
        }
        p {
            color: lightblue;
            background-color: lightcoral;
            border: 2px dashed lightcyan;
            padding: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Web Designing</h1>
    <p>This paragraph is styled using internal css</p>
</body>
</html>

EXTERNAL.html

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>External CSS</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="external.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>This Is A Heading</h1>
    <p>Learning CSS</p>
</body>
</html>

external.css

h1 {
    color: blueviolet;
    background-color: rgb(0, 255, 229);
    border: 2px dotted blue;
}
p {
    color: rgb(255, 108, 108);
    background-color: rgb(255, 169, 231);
    border: 3px dashed rgb(255, 251, 22);
    padding: 10px;
}
